ferc_filing_data.tariff_title: SDG&E Merchant 230 kV Substation Operation and Maintenance Agreement

record_data.record_plain_text: SDG&E MERCHANT 230 kV SUBSTATION OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE AGREEMENT Dated: November 6, 2015 This SDG&E Merchant 230 kV Substation Operation and Maintenance Agreement ("Agreement") is made by and between Nevada Power Company, a Nevada corporation doing business as NV Energy ("NVE"), and San Diego Gas & Electric Company, a California corporation ("SDG&E"). NVE and SDG&E may be referred to herein individually as a "Party" or collectively as the "Parties." WHEREAS, NVE and El Dorado Energy LLC ("EDE"), a subsidiary of Sempra Generation, entered into the 230kV Facilities Interconnection Agreement ("Facilities Interconnection Agreement"), dated October 1, 1998; WHEREAS, pursuant to the Facilities Interconnection Agreement, NVE and EDE agreed that NVE would maintain the entire Merchant 230 kV Substation ("Merchant") and would invoice EDE accordingly for the maintenance costs associated with Merchant; WHEREAS, SDG&E purchased EDE from Sempra Generation, with such purchase effective October 1, 2011; WHEREAS, after such purchase of EDE by SDG&E, EDE was merged into SDG&E and the Facilities Interconnection Agreement was assigned to SDG&E; WHEREAS, upon such assignment of the Facilities Interconnection Agreement to SDG&E, SDG&E became responsible for the maintenance costs associated with Merchant; WHEREAS, on September 30, 2011, NVE and SDG&E entered into the Merchant 230 kV Substation Maintenance Agreement ("Maintenance Agreement"), which was filed with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC") in Docket No. ER12-11-000 and accepted for filing effective October 1, 2011; WHEREAS, the Parties entered into the Maintenance Agreement to provide for performance by NVE of maintenance services associated with Merchant and the payment for such services by SDG&E until such time as the Facilities Interconnection Agreement is terminated due to the completion of the transfer of Merchant, all generation connected to Merchant, and two 230 kV transmission lines connecting Merchant to the Eldorado Substation into the California Independent System Operator Corporation's ("CAISO's") Balancing Authority Area ("BAA"); WHEREAS, on May 31, 2012, NVE and SDG&E amended and restated the Maintenance Agreement to provide for, among other things, the performance by NVE of both operation and maintenance activities associated with Merchant pursuant to that certain Amended and Restated Merchant 230 kV Substation Operation and Maintenance Agreement ("Amended and Restated Maintenance Agreement"), which was filed with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC") in Docket No. ER12-1902 and accepted for filing effective June 1, 2012; WHEREAS, the Parties are continuing to undertake efforts to transfer (i) the remaining NVE assets in and around Merchant, which include the 230 kV north bus, the conductors from the Merchant A-frames to pole x18740, and associated equipment and (ii) the one remaining NVE 230 kV transmission line connecting Merchant to the Eldorado Substation (the "Merchant-Eldorado Line No. 2") from NVE to SDG&E; and WHEREAS, the Parties desire to terminate the Amended and Restated Maintenance Agreement in order to terminate the services provided by NVE to SDG&E thereunder and to enter into this Agreement to provide for the performance by SDG&E of both operation and maintenance activities associated with Merchant, including the conductors from the Merchant A-frames to pole x18740, and Merchant-Eldorado Line No. 2 ("Operation Services" and "Maintenance Services") and the payment for such Operation Services and Maintenance Services by SDG&E until such time that the Facilities Interconnection Agreement is terminated due to the completion of the transfer of all of Merchant and Merchant-Eldorado Line No. 2 from NVE to SDG&E. NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises and agreements herein, including the foregoing, which are part of this Agreement and not mere recitals, the Parties, intending to be legally bound, agree on the terms and conditions as follows: 1. Maintenance Services. NVE hereby authorizes SDG&E to proceed with the performance of Maintenance Services as set forth herein. SDG&E hereby agrees to perform Maintenance Services upon the Effective Date of this Agreement and in accordance with this Agreement. Maintenance Services shall include all obligations, duties, requirements and responsibilities associated with maintaining, all of the facilities and equipment comprising the Merchant-Eldorado Line No. 2 (up to and including the last pole immediately outside of the Eldorado Substation) and all of the facilities and equipment located within the perimeter of Merchant on the high voltage side of the generator step-up transformers and the conductors from the Merchant A-frames to pole x18740, including the furnishing of all products and/or services (including, but not limited to, supervision, labor, materials, equipment and other supplies). Such Maintenance Services will extend to all metering and associated equipment located at Merchant and all communications facilities at Merchant and in the control room necessary to provide, enable, facilitate, and/or enhance protection of all such facilities and transmission lines connected to Merchant. SDG&E shall perform such Maintenance Services in accordance with the requirements set forth in Section 7 of this Agreement and inclusive of and subject to the limitations of liability set forth in this Agreement. 2. Maintenance Costs. SDG&E is responsible for all actual costs and expenses (including, but not limited to, labor, materials, overhead, and other administrative and general costs) incurred by SDG&E in the performance of Maintenance Services. 3. Operation Services. NVE authorizes SDG&E to conduct Operation Services as set forth herein. SDG&E hereby agrees to perform Operation Services upon the Effective Date of this Agreement and in accordance with the terms of this Agreement. Operation Services shall include all obligations, duties, requirements and responsibilities associated with operating the Merchant-Eldorado Line No. 2 and the 230 kV electric facilities and equipment and associated protection, metering, communications and control equipment located within the perimeter of Merchant and the conductors from the Merchant A-frames to pole x18740, exclusive of the generator step-up transformers, and interconnecting generators to Merchant. SDG&E shall perform such Operation Services in accordance with the requirements set forth in Section 7 of this Agreement and inclusive of and subject to the limitations of liability set forth in this Agreement. SDG&E assumes all North American Electric Reliability Corporation ("NERC") and Western Electricity Coordinating Council ("WECC") Reliability Standard compliance obligations associated with Merchant and Merchant-Eldorado Line No. 2. The Parties acknowledge, that until such time as the assets are transferred to SDG&E, NVE will continue to support SDG&E's obligations to demonstrate Reliability Standard compliance, by, among other things providing all maintenance records for Merchant and other information reasonably requested by SDG&E. Nothing in this Agreement shall modify SDG&E's ongoing Transmission Operator registered function obligations with respect to its Coordinated Functional Registration (CFR) Agreement with the CAISO. 4. Operation Costs. SDG&E is responsible for all of the operating costs that SDG&E incurs in the course of carrying out its obligations as an operator of the bulk electric system. 5. [Intentionally Omitted] 6. [Intentionally Omitted] 7. Standard of Work. Operation Services and Maintenance Services performed pursuant to this Agreement by SDG&E or its agents will be performed in accordance with Good Utility Practice and any applicable safety and reliability standards. As used in this Agreement, Good Utility Practice will mean any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region. 8. Term and Termination. 8.1. Term and Termination. This Agreement will be in full force and effect on the last date of the following (the "Effective Date"): (a) the date first written above, (b) the date that this Agreement is accepted for filing and made effective by FERC, (c) the date on which the transfer into the CAISO's BAA of (i) the remaining NVE assets in Merchant which include the 230 kV north bus, the conductors from the Merchant A-frames to pole x18740, and associated equipment and (ii) the Merchant-Eldorado Line No. 2, has been accepted and made effective by FERC, or (d) the date on which NVE has disconnected from Merchant both its McCullough 230kV line and its NSO 230kV line. This Agreement will be coterminous with the Facilities Interconnection Agreement. The Parties acknowledge that the Facilities Interconnection Agreement and this Agreement shall be terminated upon the transfer of all of Merchant and Merchant-Eldorado Line No. 2 from NVE to SDG&E, subject to approval by FERC. The Parties agree to work in good faith to terminate this Agreement simultaneously with the termination of the Facilities Interconnection Agreement. 8.2. FERC Filings: SDG&E will file a request for approval of the services provided under this Agreement with FERC. NVE will file a request for termination of the Amended and Restated Maintenance Agreement with FERC. The Parties agree to work in good faith to cause this request for termination and also events listed in clauses (a)-(d) of Section 8.1 to occur as concurrently as possible. 8.3. Survival. This Agreement will continue in effect after expiration or termination, to the extent necessary, to provide for final billings, billing adjustments, payments, and for the determination and/or enforcement of liability obligations arising from acts or events that occurred while this Agreement was in effect. 9. Indemnification. Each Party will at all times indemnify, defend, and hold the other Party harmless from, any and all "Losses" arising out of or resulting from the other Party's actions or inactions of its obligations under this Agreement on behalf of the indemnifying Party, except in cases of gross negligence or intentional wrongdoing by the indemnified Party. For the purposes of this Agreement, "Losses" will mean any and all damages, losses, and claims, including claims and actions relating to injury to or death of any person or damage to property, demand, suits, recoveries, costs and expenses, court costs, attorney fees, and all other obligations by or to third parties. 10. Liability. In no event will a Party be liable under any provision of this Agreement for any losses, damages, costs or expenses for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, or punitive damages, including but not limited to loss of profit or revenue, loss of the use of equipment, cost of capital, cost of temporary equipment or services, whether based in whole or in part in contract, in tort, including negligence, strict liability, or any other theory of liability; provided, however, that damages for which a Party may be liable to another party under another agreement will not be considered to be special, indirect, incidental, or consequential damages hereunder. 11. Contractors and Subcontractors. Nothing in this Agreement will prevent SDG&E from utilizing the services of any third party contractor or subcontractor as it deems appropriate to perform Maintenance Services under this Agreement; provided, however, that SDG&E will require its third party contractor and subcontractor to comply with all applicable terms and conditions of this Agreement in providing such services and SDG&E will remain primarily liable to NVE for the performance of such third party contractor and subcontractor, subject to the limitations provided in this Agreement. The creation of any third party contractor or subcontractor relationship will not relieve SDG&E of any of its obligations under this Agreement. SDG&E will be fully responsible to NVE for the acts or omissions of any third party contractor or subcontractor as if no third party contractor or subcontract relationship had been formed, subject to the limitations provided in this Agreement. Any applicable obligation imposed by this Agreement upon SDG&E will be equally binding upon, and will be construed as having application to, any third party contractor or subcontractor of SDG&E. 12. Governing Law. This Agreement will be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Nevada without giving effect to the doctrine of conflict of laws. 13. Disputes. The Parties will attempt in good faith to resolve any dispute that may arise in relation to this Agreement through amicable discussions between the Parties represented by the signatories to this Agreement, or their respective representatives, prior to either Party initiating legal action. Notwithstanding the foregoing, each Party will retain its rights to pursue any remedy available at law or equity at any time. 14. No Partnership. The covenants, obligations, and liabilities of the Parties are intended to be several and not to be joint or collective, and nothing contained in this Agreement will ever be construed to create an association, joint venture, trust or partnership, or to impose a trust or partnership covenant, obligation, or liability with regard to either Party. Each Party will be individually responsible for its own covenants, obligations, and liabilities as provided in this Agreement. Neither Party will be under the control of the other Party. Neither Party will be the agent of or have a right to bind the other Party without such other Party's express written consent. All persons employed by SDG&E in connection herewith will be employees, contractors or agents of SDG&E and not employees of NVE in any respect. 15. No Third Party Beneficiaries. This Agreement is not intended to and does not create rights, remedies, or benefits of any character whatsoever in favor of any persons, corporations, associations, or entities other than the Parties, and the obligations herein assumed are solely for the use and benefit of the Parties, their successors in interest and, where permitted, their assigns. 16. Notices. All notices, requests, demands and other communications provided under this Agreement will (unless otherwise indicated herein) be deemed sufficiently provided, given or made if delivered in person, sent by recognized overnight courier (Federal Express or its equivalent), sent by electronic mail, or sent by certified mail, postage prepaid, return receipt requested to the persons specified below. Unless otherwise specified herein, all such notices, requests, demands and other communications will be deemed effective when received whether through the mail, electronic mail, or by overnight courier service. To NVE: NV Energy Attn: Director, Transmission Policy, Contracts, and Business Services If by mail: PO Box 10100 - M/S S3B40 Reno, NV 89520-0024 If by person: 6100 Neil Road - M/S S3B40 Reno, NV 89511 E-mail: TransmissionPolicy@nvenergy.com To SDG&E: Ali Yari Director, Electric Grid Operations San Diego Gas & Electric Company 9060 Friars Rd San Diego, CA 92108 E-mail: syari@semprautilities.com Either Party may by prior written notice to the other Party designate different or additional persons or different addresses for the provision of notices hereunder. 17. Headings. The descriptive headings of the various Sections of this Agreement have been inserted for convenience of reference only and are of no significance in the interpretation or construction of this Agreement. 18. Assignment. Neither Party will assign this Agreement or any part hereof, or any rights or responsibilities hereunder without the prior written consent of the other Party, and any attempted assignment in violation hereof will be void. 19. Severability. Any provision of this Agreement prohibited or rendered unenforceable by law will be ineffective only to the extent of such prohibition or unenforceability and the remaining provisions of this Agreement will be construed in a manner to preserve to the fullest extent possible the remainder of this Agreement. 20. Entire Agreement. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties with respect to the subject matter hereof and there are no oral or written understandings, representations or commitments of any kind, express or implied, which are not expressly set forth herein. 21. Force Majeure. A Party unable to fulfill any obligation hereunder (other than an obligation to pay money when due) by reason of Force Majeure will give notice and the full particulars of such Force Majeure to the other Party in writing or by telephone as soon as reasonably possible after the occurrence of the cause relied upon. Telephone notices given pursuant to this Section will be confirmed in writing as soon as reasonably possible and will specifically state full particulars of the Force Majeure, the time and date when the Force Majeure occurred, and when the Force Majeure is reasonably expected to cease. The Party affected will exercise due diligence to remove such disability with reasonable dispatch, but will not be required to accede or agree to any provision not satisfactory to it in order to settle and terminate a strike or other labor disturbance. For the purposes of this Agreement, Force Majeure will mean any act of God, labor disturbance, act of the public enemy, war, insurrection, riot, fire, storm or flood, explosion, breakage or accident to machinery or equipment, any order, regulation or restriction imposed by governmental, military or lawfully established civilian authorities, or any other cause beyond a Party's control. A Force Majeure event does not include acts of negligence or intentional wrongdoing by the Party claiming Force Majeure. Economic hardship is not considered a Force Majeure event. 22. Nonwaiver. The failure of a Party to insist upon or enforce strict performance by the other Party of any of the terms of this Agreement or to exercise any rights herein will not be construed as a waiver or relinquishment to any extent of such Party's right to assert or rely upon such terms or rights on any future occasion. 23. Reservation of Rights. Each Party will have the right to make a unilateral filing with FERC to modify this Agreement with respect to any terms and conditions or rules or regulations under section 205 or any other applicable provision of the Federal Power Act and FERC's rules and regulations thereunder; provided, that each Party shall have the right to protest any such filing by the other Party and to participate fully in any proceeding before FERC in which such modifications may be considered. Nothing in this Agreement shall limit the rights of the Parties or of FERC under sections 205 or 206 of the Federal Power Act and FERC's rules and regulations thereunder, except to the extent that the Parties otherwise mutually agree as provided herein.
